related_questions.question: Is there a difference between ground cherries and tomatillos?
related_questions.snippet: Tomatillos produce best with two plants for pollination. They are the essential ingredient for salsa verde. Ground cherries are a smaller sweet version of tomatillos that can be eaten fresh or used in fruit salads and cobblers.
related_questions.title: Tomatillos & Ground Cherries | Portland Nursery

related_questions.question: Do ground cherries like sun or shade?
related_questions.snippet: Soil, Planting, and Care. Plant ground cherries in a garden that gets full sun. They may drop their flowers if temperatures soar above 90 °F, so a little shade in the hottest part of the day will help keep them happy. Ground cherries prefer well-drained soil with a slightly acidic pH, ranging from 6.0 to 6.8.
related_questions.title: full sun

related_questions.question: Is groundcherry edible?
related_questions.snippet: They have erect hairy green stems and typically grow to a height of 1 to 2 feet and a width of 1 to 3 feet. The ripe fleshy fruits are edible, but the rest of the plant is poisonous.
related_questions.title: Physalis heterophylla (Clammy Ground Cherry)

related_questions.question: Is ground cherry nightshade poisonous?
related_questions.snippet: Ground cherries are members of the nightshade family, containing solanine and other solanidine alkaloids. These toxins are lethal in the plant's leaves and unripe fruit. Immature berries have the highest level of toxins.
